Barbara Tuchman was the granddaughter of Henry Morgenthau, Sr. and
daughter of Maurice Wertheim, who bought &quot;The Nation&quot; for a song.
Tuchman was educated at Radcliffe College, graduating in 1935, going
on to work in Tokyo and around the world, publishing her first book in
1938, &quot;The Lost British Policy.&quot; She was perhaps more famous for &quot;The
Guns of August&quot; and &quot;Stillwell and the American Experience in China&quot;
which won her the Pulitzer in 1962 and 1971, as well as &quot;The Distant
Mirror&quot; and &quot;The March of Folly.&quot;

Along with CV Wedgwood, she is the proverbial godmother of SHWI. So,
during her globe-trotting before the Second World War, she is on the
wrong ship, at the wrong place, at the wrong time, and is washed
overboard, her body never to be found. Maurice and his wife grieve.
Tuchman's would-be husband never meets her, and his life burbles
onward.

What happens to the art of history writing without Barbara Tuchman?
Which books win instead of &quot;The Guns of August&quot; and &quot;Stillwell&quot;? What
does JFK read during the Thirteen Days?

Other thoughts?

Best

L
