I really, really hope the oft-told Tuchman story is apocryphal.
Namely, the story that it was &quot;The Guns of August&quot; that single-
handedly convinced JFK to go cautiously during the Cuban
Missile Crisis, because of the example of out-of-control
mobilization schedules. If it's true...well, fill in the rest.

If it's not true, the first effect I can think of is less nostalgia
for the Belle Epoque. _The Guns of August_ is largely
responsible for the myth of the division between the
happy, wise Belle Epoque and and the violent totalitarian
20th Century (ignoring that WWI was a Belle Epoque war,
and showed what clowns the Belle Epoque leadership
were). _The Guns of August_ doesn't entirely support
the myth, but that's the part that gets known (_The Proud
Tower_,  IIRC, doesn't support it either).

For alternate historians that JFK can admire, there's
always the usual suspects: Carlyle, Trevor-Roper,
A.J.P Taylor,.Durant, et al. Maybe Prescott too.
And Gibbon. Lots of GIbbon.

I'm not sure how pop history writing goes without her,
but then, I'm one of those who never liked Tuchman
all that much. _The Guns of August_ always struck
me as hypocritical and racist. So I'm not the best judge
here.
