And while I think that's a current or a &quot;meme&quot; run amok in certain
factions of society in the postwar world, it's not necessarily an
American one, nor one that should establish itself much as one.
Certainly, the boys and girls who grew up between 1923 and 1939 in the
USA would feel a little pressed, but their hardship doesn't constitute
a hill of beans compared to a Welsh miner or a French Jew.

Plus, generalizations are tricky creatures, Mike, and I think, while
there's going to be something going in the Anglosphere, it's certainly
possible to posit an Americocentric movement to develop in the postwar
ebullience of the US. It would be easy to tap into the 1890-1910 era
to encourage a sense of America's &quot;Republican Burden&quot; to defend the
world against lesser, less pleasant -isms that are more oppressive,
and so on. To develop a narrative sense of a particularly American
Century starting with the annexation of the Philipines on, to talk
about a rise of liberty and a defeat of one evil (imperialism) as a
dry run for the defeat of (fascism) leading to the global struggle
against (communism) without any particular handwringing for the post-
bellum era of US history. Who would want to think about Indian raids
and the Freeman's Bureau, when there are much better things to
remember? It'd blend in very well with Camelot, mind, and rachet up
all the way through 1968 or 1973.

Best

