Depends on among what kind of people. Some had
obvious reasons to be nostalgic (old-guard British
Tories, Russian Whites, etc.) Others were never
nostalgic -- Lytton Strachey became a best-seller
with a character assassination of Eminent Victorians.
Then there's the sort of neo-nostalgia you get in, say,
George Orwell, who thought the Belle Epoque was a
nightmare and a disgrace, but that it was better than
what came later.

But Tuchman has created a different kind of nostalgia.
_The Guns of August_ is pretty clearly written with
World War II in mind even though it's officially about
World War I. With phrases like &quot;the first of many
years Europeans would spend hiding in cellars,&quot; she
helped build the myth that WWI had nothing to do
with what came before, that it was part of the new age
of war and totalitarianism -- unlike what it actually was,
a war fought by Belle Epoque leaders with Belle Epoque
institutions. And the related myth that WWI swept
away the Belle Epoque by random cataclysm, unlike
what really happened -- it swept away the Belle Epoque
because nobody wanted the leadership that had created
WWI.

Again, _The Guns of August_ itself doesn't entirely
support the myth -- it makes clear that the disasters
were due to shoddy systems that put the likes of
Kaiser Bill and Rennenkampf in charge. But that's
not the part that gets remembered.
